Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` you can hand to the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol   # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>, IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;
    private IMcpClient? _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    private async Task<IMcpClient> CreateClientAsync()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient wired
        // to the in-memory test server — no real port needed.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/sse"),
                // or "/mcp" for Streamable HTTP
            },
            httpClient);           // ← inject the test HttpClient

        _client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);
        return _client;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        var client = await CreateClientAsync();

        var tools = await client.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var client = await CreateClientAsync();

        var result = await client.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.Contains(result.Content, c => c.Text == "expected output");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        if (_client is not null)
            await _client.DisposeAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your app in-process; HTTP calls never hit the network. |
| **Inject `HttpClient`** | Both `SseClientTransport` and `StreamableHttpClientTransport` accept an `HttpClient` — pass the one from `CreateClient()`. |
| **`Program` class** | Requires your server to expose a `Program` class (top-level statements do this implicitly; add `public partial class Program {}` if needed). |
| **Streamable HTTP** | If your server uses the newer Streamable HTTP transport instead of SSE, swap to `StreamableHttpClientTransport` and point at `/mcp`. |

This gives you full end-to-end MCP protocol coverage (initialize → list → call → shutdown) with fast, deterministic, in-process tests.
